    Remove a stratification from a data set

    ungroup.trackr_df.Rd

    Un-grouping a data set logically combines the different arms. In the history this joins any stratified branches and acts as a specific type of p_summary, allowing you to generate some summary statistics about the un-grouped data

    # S3 method for trackr_df
ungroup(
  x,
  ...,
  .messages = .defaultMessage(),
  .headline = .defaultHeadline(),
  .tag = NULL
)

    Arguments

    x

    - a dataframe which may be grouped (why not .data?)

    ...

    a set of dplyr summary expressions. If left blank a default of ".count=n()" will be filled in

    .messages

    - a set of glue specs. The glue code can use any summary variable defined in the ... parameter, or any global variable, or {.count}. the default is "total .count items"

    .headline

    - a headline glue spec. The glue code can use any summary variable defined in the ... parameter, or {.count}.

    .tag

    - if you want the summary data from this step in the future then give it a name with .tag.

    Value

    the .data but dplyr::ungrouped.

    Examples

    iris %>%
   p_group_by(Species) %>%
   p_comment("A test") %>%
   p_ungroup(
      my_avg = mean(Petal.Length),
      my_count = dplyr::n(),
      .messages="{my_count} items with {my_avg} petal length"
   ) %>%
   p_get()
